VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: The defect reproduces on HEAD by code inspection. ffi/src/coarse.rs:96 guards `s.count += 1` with `s.count != s.limit`, not `s.count < s.limit`; with `#[repr(C)]` `pub` fields (lines 24-27) a C or Rust caller can construct `GaleSemState { count: u32::MAX, limit: 5 }` and call gale_sem_give_v2 directly — `gale_sem_validate_v2` is a separate, optional FFI entry point, and the C header (ffi/include/gale_coarse.h:56-67) documents no precondition linking the two. `count != limit` is true, so `s.count += 1` overflows (debug: panic across the FFI boundary is UB in the C caller; release: silent wrap to 0, corrupting the semaphore and violating the module's "count up to limit" contract). The in-source comment "Verified: count < limit <= u32::MAX, no overflow" is a bare assertion: no Verus, Kani, or Rocq artifact in proofs/, src/, or ffi/src/ mentions GaleSemState, give_v2, or coarse.rs (grep confirms), and the #[allow(clippy::arithmetic_side_effects)] suppresses the only linter that would catch it. The spec-level oracle is therefore trivially valid: there is no ensures clause that covers the `count > limit` input region. The runtime PoC (unit test with `#[should_panic]`) is guaranteed to panic by Rust's documented debug-mode overflow checks. Interestingness holds: the FFI header declares no caller obligation; no hardware config or concurrency model is required; this is not a known limitation documented in artifacts/ or docs/safety/. It violates SC-3 (semaphore count bounded within [0, limit], artifacts/stpa.yaml:193) and SC-6 (overflow-checked arithmetic, line 257), and realizes H-3 (semaphore count overflow/underflow). No UCA mapping is possible because artifacts/stpa.yaml explicitly declares UCAs out of scope ("Control structure, UCAs, and loss scenarios are out of scope for this initial artifact", lines 12-13) and no safety/stpa/ucas.yaml file exists — precedent set by smp_state.verdict and userspace.verdict. Recommended new UCA when the UCA layer is authored: SEM-FFI-UCA-1 "gale_sem_give_v2 accepts `count > limit` without validation and increments, wrapping u32 or panicking; STPA UCA-type 2 (control action provided when safety constraint is violated); links: prevents SC-3, SC-6; feeds H-3 → L-2 (data integrity)". The sibling-function scope claim in the report also holds: stack_push_v2 uses `count >= capacity` (sharp), stack_pop_v2 and sem_take_v2 use `count > 0` / `count == 0` (sharp), pipe guards `used >= size` (sharp) — only give_v2 uses inequality where strict ordering was required.
